{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"79289361-1f51-48fd-acea-bf0df87b7bc1","content":"Use `Assert.ThrowsException<T>` (MSTest) or `Assert.Throws<T>` (xUnit/NUnit) instead:\n\n```csharp\n[TestMethod]\npublic void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()\n{\n    var service = new UserService();\n\n    var ex = Assert.ThrowsException<ArgumentNullException>(\n        () => service.CreateUser(null, \"John\"));\n\n    Assert.AreEqual(\"email\", ex.ParamName);\n}\n```\n\n**Why modernize:**\n- `[ExpectedException]` passes if *any* line throws, masking bugs (e.g., the constructor could throw instead of `CreateUser`).\n- `Assert.ThrowsException` pinpoints the exact call and lets you inspect the exception (message, `ParamName`, inner exception, etc.).\n- The test fails immediately if no exception is thrown, with a clear error message.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b71f911d-933d-4627-805c-24cce65cc81c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about modernizing a C# test that uses the `[ExpectedException]` attribute. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":269,"requestId":"083B:152A04:D2C146:F38F0C:69EAC5E9"},"id":"8abb2426-03e7-4c46-8e2a-2adc5452d67a","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:22:56.236Z","parentId":"fbd4f0d6-7200-4e2a-8e6e-ff2bb63c26ea"}
